1. Problem Statement
Water is a limited and valuable resource, yet schools often consume large amounts daily through washrooms, drinking water stations, cleaning, gardening, and canteens. Much of this water is wasted due to leaks, inefficient fixtures, and lack of monitoring.
At our school, water usage has increased with the growing number of students and daily activities. If water consumption continues at the current rate, it will lead to higher costs and unnecessary environmental impact. Therefore, there is a need to design a practical water conservation system that reduces wastage while remaining affordable and easy to implement.
2. Research and Data Collection
To understand the current situation, interviews were conducted with school administrative staff and maintenance personnel.
Findings from Interviews
The school uses municipal water supply
Water is mainly used for:
Washrooms (toilets and taps)
Drinking water coolers
Cleaning classrooms
Gardening
No automated monitoring system is currently installed
Leaking taps are reported occasionally but not detected immediately
Estimated Daily Water Usage
From staff estimates:
Average water usage per student ≈ 90 litres/day
Total number of students ≈ 250
Calculation
Daily water consumption = Number of students × Water per student
Daily water consumption = 250 × 90
Daily water consumption = 22,500 litres/day
This shows that even small reductions per student can save thousands of litres daily.
3. Proposed Solutions
Solution 1: Sensor-Based Automatic Taps
Description:
Install motion-sensor taps in washrooms to prevent taps being left open.
How it works:
Water flows only when hands are detected
Automatically stops after use
Estimated Cost:
₹3,000 per tap × 30 taps = ₹90,000
Benefits:
Reduces water wastage by up to 30–40%
Improves hygiene
Long-term cost savings
Solution 2: Rainwater Harvesting System
Description:
Collect rainwater from rooftops and store it in underground tanks.
How it works:
Rainwater flows through gutters into a filtration system
Stored water is used for gardening and cleaning
Estimated Cost:
Storage tank + filters + pipes ≈ ₹1,20,000
Benefits:
Saves thousands of litres during monsoon season
Reduces dependency on municipal water
Environmentally sustainable
Solution 3: Smart Water Meter & Leak Detection
Description:
Install a digital water meter to monitor daily water usage and detect leaks early.
How it works:
Tracks real-time water consumption
Alerts staff if abnormal usage is detected
Estimated Cost:
Smart meter + installation ≈ ₹45,000
Benefits:
Prevents unnoticed water loss
Encourages responsible water usage
Helps track conservation progress
